<b>LAON  IS  PEACEFUL  WHILE  GUNS  ROAR</b>

&quot;This weak fortress town, built on the top of a high and solitary hill that affords a clear sweep of the country for miles, is typical of life in France under the German occupation. The fine old cathedral, with its four square  towers, and, in fact, the whole town, has not served as a target for the heavy artillerists, owing their immunity to the weakness of the fortifications and the consequent fact that the English didn't find it desirable to linger there on their retreat after Mons [Belgium] in the early days of the war.&quot;

Laon owes its current importance to being a main station on one of the trunk lines of communication.

The article goes on to point out the &quot;new cosmopolitanism&quot; the war has brought. Germans are now firing French ammunition from Belgian cannon on Englishmen, While in the town itself, the shops are all open and busy, German trains arrive on time, and a genuine Munich beer can be bought ... a change from the earlier days in the war of having to pay three bottles of (French) champagne for a half-pound of butter, while three bottles of red wine was the going price for one cigarette.
&nbsp;

From <a href="http://digital.library.upenn.edu/women/adami/camc/camc.html" rel="nofollow">digital.library.upenn.edu/women/adami/camc/camc.html</a>
 War Story of the Canadian Army Medical Corps.   By George Adami. 1918
&quot;With reference to the medical units other than the field ambulances and No. 1 General Hospital, and their activities during the period of training; to No. 2 Stationary Hospital was granted the distinction of being the first of all Canadian units to place foot upon French soil. This unit, under Lieutenant-Colonel Shillington, after the inspection by Their Majesties the King and Queen two days previously, left the Plain on November 6th, 1914. At Southampton the O.C. was detained by arrangements concerning the nursing sisters, and thus it devolved upon Major H. C. S. Elliot, the second in command, to take the unit across the Channel to Havre. For a few days it was billeted at Boulogne. On November 27th it opened up the well-known Hôtel du Golf at Le Touquet, on the dunes near Paris Plage, as a hospital of three hundred beds – the first of a series of Canadian base hospitals along the French coast between Boulogne and Dieppe. &quot;
  and
&quot;The O.C., Lieutenant-Colonel A. T. Shillington, and Major F. McK. Bell had both of them been on the staff of St. Luke's Hospital in that city; the Adjutant, Captain C. A. Young, on the staff of the Ottawa General Hospital. Two of the nine officers came from Toronto, one, Major H. C. S. Elliott, from Coburg. The only officer not an Ontario man was the Quartermaster, Captain T. S. Walker, from Prince Edward Island. &quot;

The golf club, founded by Stoneham, was the location of the 2nd Canadian Stationary Hospital in neighboring pictures.
&quot;Le Touquet, some few miles beyond Étaples and on the outskirts of the small but very fashionable watering-place, Paris Plage, had before the war been well known to golf enthusiasts as possessing on its sand dunes the finest and best laid out golf course on the Continent of Europe, with a spacious Golf Club House, and in its immediate neighbourhood a small and cheerful Hôtel du Golf and several villas occupied season after season by enthusiasts of the game. The owner of the hotel, Mr. Stoneham, gave it over with great goodwill, and, what is more, donated an operating table for the purposes of the unit. &quot;
