&quot;That the man who made the hydroareoplane possible was not Glen H. Curtiss but Albert S. Janin, a poor cabinetmaker of Staten Island, was the summary decision rendered by the board of examiners of the patent of fice. Air. Curtiss began experimenting with a canoe device in 1910. In the controversy that followed the use of the present method it came out that Mr. Janin had really produced the successful device in 1909, but that his poverty prevented him from testing his plans with an actual aeroplane. It is now shown that Janin endured hardships and ridicule and in the years he was working on his water flyer he was made the butt of many who looked upon him as unbalanced by one idea. Mr. Janin's victory will probably make him wealthy immediately, as an order from one of the European belligerents for 200 hydro-aeroplanes is awaiting any manufacturer who is willing to furnish security that they can be delivered. Lawyers for Mr. Curtiss, it is learned, had decided to appeal the case to the Commissioner of Patents, and further to the United States Court of Appeals, if the Commissioner sustains the examiners' decision.&quot;
