New York Times headline, 2 January 1915:  &quot;Woman Taxi Driver Invades Broadway; New York's First Feminine Chauffeur Starts Business on New Year's Day.; Men Rivals are Friendly; She Wears a Leopard-Skin Hat and Stole--Gets Big Tip from Initial Fare.&quot;

Story says of the rest of her ensemble:  Even before it was een that the driver was wearing a skirt, her appearance attracted attention.  She wore on her head a huge round hat of leopard skin, and around her neck and over her shoulders the yellow and black spotted pelt of the same animal...She had on a brown skirt that came down just below the tops of her high tan boots, and a brown jacket.  Her forearms were lost in black leather gloves.&quot;

Wilma K. Russey had a chauffeur's license, and was employed as a mechanic by Dalton's Garage at 354 W. 50th St.

She's mentioned in this 1997 MA thesis, Kimberly Berry, &quot;The Experience and Expression of Gender among Women Taxi Drivers&quot;:
<a href="http://www.taxi-library.org/nolady.htm" rel="nofollow">www.taxi-library.org/nolady.htm</a>
She also turns up in Virginia Scharff, <i>Taking the Wheel:  Women and the Coming of the Motor Age</i> (UNM Press 1999):  85.

